			<h3>Features</h3>
			<ul class="std_list">
				<li>Uses Paypal subscription buttons</li>
				<li>Add as many Paypal buttons as you like</li>
				<li>Display the buttons in any order you like</li>
				<li>Description text for each button</li>
				<li>Activate/Deactivate specific buttons without having to delete them</li>
				<li>All transactions visible per blog</li>
				<li>Subscribers can be your affiliates</li>
				<li>Offer flat or percentage commissions for affiliate referrals</li>
				<li>Configure specific commissions per subscription button</li>
				<li>Option to pay reoccurring commissions per button</li>
				<li>Choice of paying affiliate commissions instantly, daily, weekly, and monthly</li>
				<li>Configurable affiliate cookie lifespan</li>
				<li>Configurable Paypal email address used for affiliate payouts if you want it different from your subscription buttons</li>
				<li>Subscriber can change Paypal email address affiliate commissions</li>
				<li>Supports sub-domain or sub-directory MU setups</li>
				<li>Support for Paypal trial periods</li>
				<li>Manual sign-up and payment entry.  This does not do Paypal payments, but it does allow you to give out trial memberships or grant access when payments are handled outside the system.</li>
				<li>6 Levels of affiliate commisions.  Up to 6 affiliates can get paid a flat or percent rate when a new blog is signed up.</li>
				<li>Allow/Deny specific plug-ins based on subscription level.</li>
				<li>Allow/Deny specific themes based on subscription level.</li>
				<li>When a blog owner's subscription has expired or has been cancelled, you now have the option of displaying a message to visitors of that blog or redirecting them to another web page.</li>
				<li>Optional logging of all Paypal data direct to file so you can trace Paypal errors and plug-in integration issues.</li>
				<li>Enable Paypal buttons based on start and end date/time</li>
				<li>Affiliate reports</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>How it Works...</h3>
			<ol class="std_list">
				<li>When your Wordpress MU blog owners log-in to the admin area, they will be presented with a list of Paypal Subscribe buttons that you create.</li>
				<li>After they return from their round-trip to Paypal to sign-up and pay, they will be brought back to the same page.</li>
				<li>At the same time Paypal will notify a special script in your blog that they have paid, how much, and for how long the subscription will last.</li>
				<li>Your blog owner will then be able to continue to the admin area.</li>
				<li>In the admin area they will have a page that shows them their affiliate URL.</li>
				<li>If or when their subscription has expired, they will be denied access to their admin area and will see your Paypal Subscribe buttons again.</li>
			</ol>

